PrzeprowadzÄ™ teraz tuning parametrÃ³w na zbiorze bank_marketing

ind <- sample(dim(bank_marketing_dat)[1], round(0.7*dim(bank_marketing_dat)[1]))
data_train <- bank_marketing_dat[ind,]
data_test <- bank_marketing_dat[-ind,]

classif_task_pars <- makeClassifTask(id="radnomSearch", data = data_train, target = bank_marketing$target.features)

getParamSet(makeLearner("classif.h2o.gbm"))
##                           Type len   Def      Constr Req Tunable Trafo
## ntrees                 integer   -    50    1 to Inf   -    TRUE     -
## max_depth              integer   -     5    1 to Inf   -    TRUE     -
## min_rows               integer   -    10    1 to Inf   -    TRUE     -
## learn_rate             numeric   -   0.1      0 to 1   -    TRUE     -
## nbins                  integer   -    20    1 to Inf   -    TRUE     -
## nbins_cats             integer   -  1024    1 to Inf   -    TRUE     -
## balance_classes        logical   - FALSE           -   -    TRUE     -
## max_after_balance_size integer   -     1    0 to Inf   -    TRUE     -
## seed                   integer   -     - -Inf to Inf   -   FALSE     -
ps = makeParamSet(
  makeNumericParam("learn_rate", lower = 0.005, upper = 0.01),
  makeDiscreteParam("ntrees", values = 200:500),
  makeDiscreteParam("max_depth", values = 7:20),
  makeDiscreteParam("min_rows", values = 2:15),
  makeDiscreteParam("nbins", values = 4:64)
)

ctrl = makeTuneControlRandom(maxit = 10L)

res = tuneParams("classif.h2o.gbm", task = classif_task_pars, resampling = cv,
                    par.set = ps, control = ctrl)

lrn = setHyperPars(makeLearner("classif.h2o.gbm", predict.type = "prob"), par.vals = res$x) 
m = train(lrn, classif_task_pars)
p <- predict(m, newdata = data_test)

PoniewaÅ¼ nie udaÅ‚o mi siÄ™ poprawiÄ‡ modelu po uzyskaniu prawdziwych etykiet kilku obserwacji postanowiÅ‚em lepiej zapoznaÄ‡ siÄ™ z tuningiem parametrÃ³w h2o.gbm. Na podstawie artykuÅ‚u https://github.com/h2oai/h2o-3/blob/master/h2o-docs/src/product/tutorials/gbm/gbmTuning.Rmd oraz https://www.analyticsvidhya.com/blog/2016/02/complete-guide-parameter-tuning-gradient-boosting-gbm-python/ przeprowadziÅ‚em dodatkowy tuning przy uÅ¼yciu biblioteki h2o.

5.1 Kluczowe parametry

  1. ntrees - generalnie im wiÄ™ksza liczba drzew tym wiÄ™ksza dokÅ‚adnoÅ›Ä‡
  2. learn_rate - mniejsza wartoÅ›Ä‡ daje lepsze wyniki, jednak wymaga wiÄ™kszej liczby drzew. Ten parametr kontroluje jak duÅ¼y wpÅ‚yw na wynik modelu ma kaÅ¼de kolejne drzewo
  3. max_depth - maksymalna gÅ‚Ä™bokoÅ›Ä‡ pojedynczego drzewa ogranicza zdolnoÅ›Ä‡ modelu do przeuczenia
  4. nbins - okreÅ›la liczbÄ™ kontenerÃ³w koniecnzych do stworzenia histogramu, ktÃ³ry jest nastÄ™pnie dzielony w optymalnym punkcjie
  5. min_rows - minimalna liczba obserwacji zawartych w liÅ›ciu

5.2 Zakres maxdepth

Parametr max_depth ma duÅ¼y wpÅ‚yw na trening modelu, a wartoÅ›ci optymalne sÄ… mocno powiÄ…zane ze zbiorem danych.

Wynik dla domyÅ›lnych parametrÃ³w bez uÅ¼ycia mlr

hyper_params = list( max_depth = seq(1,29,2) )

grid <- h2o.grid(
  ## hyper parameters
  hyper_params = hyper_params,
  
  ## full Cartesian hyper-parameter search
  search_criteria = list(strategy = "Cartesian"),
  
  ## which algorithm to run
  algorithm="gbm",
  
  ## identifier for the grid, to later retrieve it
  grid_id="depth_grid",
  
  ## standard model parameters
  x = predictors, 
  y = response, 
  training_frame = train, 
  validation_frame = test,
  
  ## more trees is better if the learning rate is small enough 
  ## here, use "more than enough" trees - we have early stopping
  ntrees = 10000,                                                            
  
  ## smaller learning rate is better
  ## since we have learning_rate_annealing, we can afford to start with a bigger learning rate
  learn_rate = 0.02,                                                         
  
  ## learning rate annealing: learning_rate shrinks by 1% after every tree 
  ## (use 1.00 to disable, but then lower the learning_rate)
  learn_rate_annealing = 0.995,                                               
  
  ## sample 80% of rows per tree
  sample_rate = 0.9,                                                       
  ## sample 80% of columns per split
  col_sample_rate = 0.9, 
  
  ## fix a random number generator seed for reproducibility
  seed = 1234,                                                             
  
  ## early stopping once the validation AUC doesn't improve by at least 0.01% for 5 consecutive scoring events
  stopping_rounds = 5,
  stopping_tolerance = 1e-4,
  stopping_metric = "AUC", 
  
  ## score every 10 trees to make early stopping reproducible (it depends on the scoring interval)
  score_tree_interval = 10                                                
)
## by default, display the grid search results sorted by increasing logloss (since this is a classification task)
                                                                   
## sort the grid models by decreasing AUC
sortedGrid <- h2o.getGrid("depth_grid", sort_by="auc", decreasing = TRUE)    

## find the range of max_depth for the top 5 models
topDepths = sortedGrid@summary_table$max_depth[1:5]                       
minDepth = min(as.numeric(topDepths))
maxDepth = max(as.numeric(topDepths))
minDepth
## [1] 11
maxDepth
## [1] 19

MajÄ…c ten przedziaÅ‚ przeprowadziÅ‚em tuning parametrÃ³w dla lepiej zdefiniowanych przedziaÅ‚Ã³w. Nie uzyskaÅ‚em jednak wyraÅºnej poprawy.

hyper_params = list( 
  ## restrict the search to the range of max_depth established above
  max_depth = seq(minDepth,maxDepth,1),                                      
  
  ## search a large space of row sampling rates per tree
  sample_rate = seq(0.5,1,0.01),                                             
  
  ## search a large space of column sampling rates per split
  col_sample_rate = seq(0.5,1,0.01),                                         
  
  ## search a large space of column sampling rates per tree
  col_sample_rate_per_tree = seq(0.8,1,0.01),                                
  
  ## search a large space of how column sampling per split should change as a function of the depth of the split
  col_sample_rate_change_per_level = seq(0.8,1.1,0.01),                      
  
  ## search a large space of the number of min rows in a terminal node
  min_rows = 2^seq(0,log2(nrow(train))-1,1),                                 
  
  ## search a large space of the number of bins for split-finding for continuous and integer columns
  nbins = 2^seq(4,10,1),                                                     
  
  ## search a large space of the number of bins for split-finding for categorical columns
  nbins_cats = 2^seq(4,12,1),                                                
  
  ## search a few minimum required relative error improvement thresholds for a split to happen
  min_split_improvement = c(0,1e-8,1e-6),                               
  
  ## try all histogram types (QuantilesGlobal and RoundRobin are good for numeric columns with outliers)
  histogram_type = c("UniformAdaptive","QuantilesGlobal","RoundRobin")       
)
search_criteria = list(
  ## Random grid search
  strategy = "RandomDiscrete",      
  
  ## limit the runtime to 60 minutes
  max_runtime_secs = 600,         
  
  ## build no more than 100 models
  max_models = 200,                  
  
  ## random number generator seed to make sampling of parameter combinations reproducible
  seed = 12,                        
  
  ## early stopping once the leaderboard of the top 5 models is converged to 0.1% relative difference
  stopping_rounds = 5,                
  stopping_metric = "AUC",
  stopping_tolerance = 1e-5
)
grid <- h2o.grid(
  ## hyper parameters
  hyper_params = hyper_params,
  
  ## hyper-parameter search configuration (see above)
  search_criteria = search_criteria,
  
  ## which algorithm to run
  algorithm = "gbm",
  
  ## identifier for the grid, to later retrieve it
  grid_id = "final_grid", 
  
  ## standard model parameters
  x = predictors, 
  y = response, 
  training_frame = train, 
  validation_frame = test,
  
  ## more trees is better if the learning rate is small enough
  ## use "more than enough" trees - we have early stopping
  ntrees = 10000,                                                            
  
  ## smaller learning rate is better
  ## since we have learning_rate_annealing, we can afford to start with a bigger learning rate
  learn_rate = 0.01,                                                         
  
  ## learning rate annealing: learning_rate shrinks by 1% after every tree 
  ## (use 1.00 to disable, but then lower the learning_rate)
  learn_rate_annealing = 1,                                               
  
  ## early stopping based on timeout (no model should take more than 1 hour - modify as needed)
  max_runtime_secs = 600,                                                 
  
  ## early stopping once the validation AUC doesn't improve by at least 0.01% for 5 consecutive scoring events
  stopping_rounds = 5, stopping_tolerance = 1e-6, stopping_metric = "AUC", 
  
  ## score every 10 trees to make early stopping reproducible (it depends on the scoring interval)
  score_tree_interval = 10,                                                
  
  ## base random number generator seed for each model (automatically gets incremented internally for each model)
  seed = 12                                                         
)
## Sort the grid models by AUC
sortedGrid <- h2o.getGrid("final_grid", sort_by = "auc", decreasing = TRUE)    


for (i in 1:5) {
  gbm <- h2o.getModel(sortedGrid@model_ids[[i]])
  print(h2o.auc(h2o.performance(gbm, valid = TRUE)))
}
## [1] 0.8992601
## [1] 0.8992601
## [1] 0.8973838

## [1] 0.8969044

PorÃ³wnanie moich parametrÃ³w i domyÅ›lnych dla zbiorÃ³w podobnych przy uÅ¼yciu benchmark

cv <- makeResampleDesc("CV", iters = 5)
